  <content>
    <title>Multi-Agent Design Patterns</title>
    <summary>Eight essential design patterns enable orchestration of multi-agent systems in enterprise workflows. These patterns — Sequential Pipeline, Parallel Fan-Out/Gather, Hierarchical Decomposition, Generator-Critic, Loop Pattern, Human-in-the-Loop, Router Pattern, and Blackboard Pattern — provide reusable solutions for different coordination and quality requirements.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>Single all-purpose agents cannot handle complex enterprise workflows efficiently. As enterprises adopt AI agents (1,445% surge in inquiries Q1 2024 to Q2 2025), they need proven patterns for orchestrating specialized agents. Design patterns codify best practices, reduce reinvention, and make systems maintainable.</p>
      <p>Different problems have different structure. A sequential workflow (research → implement → test) differs from parallel analysis (multiple reviewers) or iterative refinement (generator-critic). Matching the pattern to the task structure determines success or failure.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Enterprise workflow automation where no single agent has all required expertise — use Hierarchical Decomposition.</item>
        <item>Content or code quality checks that must catch every error, not just obvious ones — use Generator-Critic.</item>
        <item>Multi-dimensional analysis tasks where independent perspectives reduce blind spots — use Parallel Fan-Out/Gather.</item>
        <item>Long-horizon tasks that require iterative refinement with feedback loops — use Loop Pattern.</item>
        <item>Workflows requiring human sign-off before irreversible steps — use Human-in-the-Loop.</item>
        <item>Dynamic routing across multiple knowledge domains based on query content — use Router Pattern.</item>
        <item>Knowledge synthesis tasks where agents share a common workspace — use Blackboard Pattern.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Simple retrieval or single-step generation — pattern overhead adds cost with no quality gain.</item>
        <item>Latency-critical paths where multiple sequential agent calls are unacceptable.</item>
        <item>Tasks without clear decomposition axes — forcing patterns onto unstructured tasks creates artificial fragmentation.</item>
        <item>Early prototyping phases where debugging orchestration complexity is not yet warranted.</item>
        <item>Single-domain problems where one specialized agent is sufficient.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>
    <section name="The Eight Essential Design Patterns">
      <term name="Sequential Pipeline">Assembly line: each agent processes the output of the previous stage. Use for linear workflows (research → implement → test). Each stage must handle partial or malformed output from the previous stage; no stage can "reach back" to request clarification.</term>
      <term name="Parallel Fan-Out/Gather">Spawn parallel agents, then synthesize their results. Use for PR reviews, multi-aspect analysis. Synthesis step is a single call — a weak synthesizer loses value from good parallel work.</term>
      <term name="Hierarchical Decomposition">High-level agent decomposes a goal into subtasks and delegates to workers. Use for complex goal breakdown. Plan quality determines everything; a poor planner produces overlapping or incomplete subtasks.</term>
      <term name="Generator and Critic">One agent creates, another validates against a quality rubric. Use for quality-critical content. Generator and critic from the same model will miss the same failure modes.</term>
      <term name="Loop Pattern">Iterative refinement cycles until a success criterion is met. Use for self-improving outputs. Without a verifiable exit criterion, loops run to the iteration cap and exit with partial quality.</term>
      <term name="Human-in-the-Loop">Workflow pauses for explicit human approval before proceeding. Use for high-stakes decisions. In async pipelines, the human approval step must block the workflow, not just log a request.</term>
      <term name="Router Pattern">Dynamic agent selection based on task content. Use for multi-domain queries. Routing based on LLM classification introduces latency; misrouting is silent.</term>
      <term name="Blackboard Pattern">Shared workspace where agents collaborate. Use for knowledge synthesis. Concurrent writes require locking or append-only semantics to avoid data races.</term>
    </section>
    <section name="Sequential Pipeline Pattern">
      <p>Each agent processes the output of the previous stage in a linear assembly line.</p>
      <example type="good" title="Sequential Pipeline Implementation">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
Researcher → Implementer → Tester → Documenter

Each stage:
- Receives input from previous stage
- Processes it
- Passes output to next stage
]]></code>
      </example>
      <rule>
        <statement>Each stage must be robust to partial or malformed output from the previous stage.</statement>
        <rationale>Stages cannot reach back to request clarification. Build error handling at each stage.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Assuming previous stage output will be perfectly formatted.</description>
        <reason>Real LLM outputs are messy. Add validation and error recovery at each stage.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="Parallel Fan-Out/Gather Pattern">
      <p>Spawn multiple agents in parallel, each handling an independent subtask, then gather and synthesize results.</p>
      <example type="good" title="Parallel Analysis">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
Task: Analyze security of code submission

Fan-Out:
- Security Auditor → Check for vulnerabilities
- Performance Analyst → Check for inefficiencies
- Code Quality Reviewer → Check for style and maintainability

Gather:
- Synthesizer → Combine all three perspectives into one report
]]></code>
      </example>
      <rule>
        <statement>Cap the number of parallel workers at 5-8; more workers rarely improve synthesis quality.</statement>
      </rule>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Weak synthesizer loses value from good parallel work.</description>
        <reason>Parallel quality only matters if synthesis is strong. Use an Opus-grade synthesizer.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="Hierarchical Decomposition Pattern">
      <p>A high-level agent breaks down a complex goal into subtasks, assigns them to workers, and integrates results.</p>
      <example type="good" title="Hierarchical Project Breakdown">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
Planner: "Build a web app"

Decomposition:
- Backend Engineer: Build API endpoints
- Frontend Engineer: Build UI components
- QA Lead: Prepare test plan
- DevOps Engineer: Set up CI/CD

Integration: Planner synthesizes all outputs
]]></code>
      </example>
      <rule>
        <statement>Plan quality determines everything. Invest in a strong planner.</statement>
        <rationale>A poor planner produces overlapping tasks, gaps, or impossible requirements. Use Opus for planning.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="Generator and Critic Pattern">
      <p>One agent generates output; another validates it against a quality rubric and provides feedback for refinement.</p>
      <example type="good" title="Generator-Critic Loop">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
def generator_critic_loop(generator_fn, critic_fn, task, max_iterations=3):
    output = generator_fn(task)
    for _ in range(max_iterations):
        feedback = critic_fn(output)
        if not feedback.get("failed"):
            return output  # all rubric items passed
        output = generator_fn(f"{task}\n\nRevise based on feedback:\n{feedback['failed']}")
    return output  # best effort after max iterations
]]></code>
      </example>
      <rule>
        <statement>Use a different base model or temperature for critic vs. generator to reduce shared blind spots.</statement>
        <rationale>Claude as critic for GPT-generated output (and vice versa) catches more errors than same-model pairs.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Define the quality rubric explicitly as JSON schema with pass/fail criteria.</statement>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Generator-Critic Prompt">
        <code lang="xml"><![CDATA[
<role>Critic</role>
<quality_rubric>{{rubric_items}}</quality_rubric>
<generated_output>{{generator_output}}</generated_output>
<instruction>
Evaluate the output against each rubric item.
Return JSON: {"passed": ["item1"], "failed": [{"item": "item2", "reason": "...", "fix": "..."}]}
</instruction>
]]></code>
      </example>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Generator and critic from the same base model converge on shared blind spots.</description>
        <reason>LLMs trained on the same data share biases. Use different models or fine-tuned variants.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="Loop Pattern">
      <p>Iteratively refine output until a success criterion is met.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Define the exit criterion as a function that returns True/False, not an LLM judgment — deterministic exits prevent runaway loops.</statement>
      </rule>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Loop exits at max_iterations regardless of quality.</description>
        <reason>Always inspect the final output; do not assume max iterations implies a passing result.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="Human-in-the-Loop Pattern">
      <p>Workflow pauses for explicit human approval before irreversible steps (write to DB, send message, deploy).</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Surface the human gate with a complete action summary, not just a yes/no prompt.</statement>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>In async pipelines, the human approval step must block the workflow, not just log a request. Use LangGraph's interrupt_before or an explicit polling mechanism.</statement>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="Router Pattern">
      <p>Dynamic agent selection based on query content. Routes incoming queries to the most appropriate specialist.</p>
      <example type="good" title="Router Prompt">
        <code lang="xml"><![CDATA[
<role>Router</role>
<available_experts>{{expert_list_with_domains}}</available_experts>
<query>{{user_query}}</query>
<instruction>Select the most appropriate expert. Return JSON: {"expert": "name", "rationale": "..."}</instruction>
]]></code>
      </example>
      <rule>
        <statement>Log every routing decision with the query, chosen expert, and rationale for monitoring routing accuracy over time.</statement>
      </rule>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Router misclassification sends queries to the wrong expert with no automatic recovery.</description>
        <reason>Add a confidence score to routing decisions and fall back to a generalist agent below threshold.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="Blackboard Pattern">
      <p>Agents collaborate on a shared workspace, reading and writing contributions incrementally.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Use append-only writes to the shared workspace; never allow agents to delete or overwrite others' contributions.</statement>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Use named, agent-scoped keys or an explicit merge protocol to avoid concurrency conflicts.</statement>
      </rule>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Concurrent writes to shared blackboard keys. Last write wins silently.</description>
        <reason>Use immutable append semantics or explicit locking to prevent data loss.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="Pattern Selection Guidance">
      <p>Match pattern to task structure:</p>
      <list>
        <item>Linear workflows with clear stages → Sequential Pipeline</item>
        <item>Multiple independent perspectives needed → Parallel Fan-Out/Gather</item>
        <item>Large goal needs decomposition → Hierarchical Decomposition</item>
        <item>Quality must be guaranteed → Generator-Critic</item>
        <item>Output needs refinement → Loop Pattern</item>
        <item>Irreversible action requires approval → Human-in-the-Loop</item>
        <item>Task type determines agent selection → Router Pattern</item>
        <item>Collaborative knowledge synthesis → Blackboard Pattern</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="Framework Comparison">
      <p>Several frameworks implement these patterns:</p>
      <term name="LangGraph">State-machine graphs for loop, router, and blackboard patterns. Persistent state, built-in human-in-loop. Recommended for complex patterns requiring state.</term>
      <term name="CrewAI">Role-based teams for hierarchical and collaborative patterns. Low setup complexity.</term>
      <term name="AutoGen">Conversation-centric patterns (debate, collaborative). Microsoft backed.</term>
      <term name="Google Vertex AI Agent Builder">ADK-native; implements all 8 Google ADK patterns natively.</term>
      <term name="AgentFlow">Low-code canvas, production-ready for simple to moderate patterns.</term>
    </section>
    <section name="Enterprise Adoption">
      <p>Adoption is accelerating:</p>
      <list>
        <item>Gartner: 1,445% surge in multi-agent inquiries (Q1 2024 to Q2 2025)</item>
        <item>Prediction: 40% of enterprise apps will include AI agents by 2026 (Gartner)</item>
        <item>IDC: 80% of workplace apps will have AI copilots by 2026</item>
      </list>
      <note>Rapid adoption means tooling is maturing quickly, but production battle-testing is still limited. Treat framework docs as authoritative; blog tutorials may be outdated by months.</note>
    </section>
    <section name="Recommended Subagents">
      <list>
        <item>pattern-selector — classifies task against the 8 patterns and returns recommended pattern + rationale; uses Sonnet.</item>
        <item>planner — Hierarchical Decomposition: decomposes goal into subtask assignments; uses Opus.</item>
        <item>domain-expert-worker — executes a focused subtask in a specific domain; uses Sonnet.</item>
        <item>critic — Generator-Critic: validates output against quality rubric, returns structured feedback; uses Sonnet.</item>
        <item>router — Router Pattern: classifies query and dispatches to correct specialist agent; uses Haiku.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="CLI Tools and Installation">
      <term name="LangGraph">State-machine graphs for multi-agent patterns. Install: pip install langgraph. Docs: langchain-ai.github.io/langgraph</term>
      <term name="CrewAI">Role-based teams. Install: pip install crewai. Docs: crewai.com</term>
      <term name="AutoGen">Conversation-centric multi-agent. Install: pip install pyautogen. Docs: microsoft.github.io/autogen</term>
      <term name="AgentOps">Observability for all patterns — cost, latency, trace. Install: pip install agentops. Docs: agentops.ai</term>
      <term name="Prefect">Workflow orchestration with retries and scheduling. Install: pip install prefect. Docs: docs.prefect.io</term>
    </section>
    <section name="Managed Services">
      <term name="LangGraph Cloud">Persistent state for loop and blackboard patterns; built-in human-in-loop. SaaS.</term>
      <term name="CrewAI Enterprise">Managed hierarchical and collaborative crew execution. SaaS.</term>
      <term name="Google Vertex AI Agent Builder">ADK-native; implements all 8 Google ADK patterns. SaaS.</term>
      <term name="AutoGen Studio">Visual builder for conversational and generator-critic patterns. OSS.</term>
      <term name="LangSmith">Full trace per pattern step; invaluable for debugging routing errors. SaaS.</term>
    </section>
    <section name="Best Practices">
      <list>
        <item>Match pattern to task structure before writing any code — the wrong pattern costs more to fix than to prevent.</item>
        <item>Use a different base model or temperature for critic vs. generator to reduce shared blind spots.</item>
        <item>Cap the number of parallel workers at 5-8; more workers rarely improve synthesis quality.</item>
        <item>Surface the human gate with a complete action summary, not just a yes/no prompt.</item>
        <item>Define the exit criterion as a function that returns True/False, not an LLM judgment.</item>
        <item>Log every routing decision with the query, chosen expert, and rationale for monitoring routing accuracy.</item>
        <item>Use append-only writes to the shared workspace; never allow agents to delete or overwrite others' contributions.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="AI-Agent Gotchas">
      <list>
        <item>Critic shares training data with generator — generator and critic from the same model will miss the same failure modes. Consider using Claude as critic for GPT-generated output or vice versa.</item>
        <item>Loop exit without success — the loop pattern exits at max_iterations regardless of quality. Always inspect the final output; do not assume max iterations implies a passing result.</item>
        <item>Router misclassification — if the router sends a query to the wrong expert, downstream errors are silent. Add a confidence score to routing decisions and fall back to a generalist agent below threshold.</item>
        <item>Human-in-loop synchronization — in async pipelines, the human approval step must block the workflow, not just log a request.</item>
        <item>Blackboard concurrency — if two agents write conflicting updates to the same blackboard key, the last write wins silently. Use named, agent-scoped keys or an explicit merge protocol.</item>
        <item>Framework dependency — framework-specific DSLs (CrewAI, LangGraph) lock in orchestration logic; switching frameworks later is costly.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <templates>
      <template path="templates/generator-critic-loop.py" purpose="Generator-Critic loop with quality rubric validation"/>
      <template path="templates/router-pattern.py" purpose="Router for dynamic agent selection based on query"/>
      <template path="templates/hierarchical-decomposition.py" purpose="Planner that decomposes goal into subtasks"/>
      <template path="templates/human-in-loop-gate.py" purpose="Human approval checkpoint before irreversible action"/>
    </templates>
